<text>Potential Energy Curves and Activation Energy: Potential Energy Curves and Reactions
Below is a graph of the potential energy associated with the reaction you watched on the previous page. Notice that when the atom and molecule collide there is an increase of potential energy. You should also have noticed that every collision didn&apos;t result in a reaction. The atom and molecule had to hit each other several times, because they will only react when they hit hard enough and at the right angle. If they hit hard enough and at the right angle, enough kinetic energy will be converted to potential energy so that the old bond can break and the new bond can form. When the new bond formed it was stronger and more stable, so some potential energy was converted to kinetic energy, as you can see, by looking at the graph next to the model.

         
     </text>
